    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated pedicle screw F1717 compression-bending FEA) is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) All three primary QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) show FEA-to-experiment agreement within 2.5%, well below the 10% acceptance bound, with E/u_val values of 0.81, 0.94, and 0.52, all below the 1.96 threshold. (2) Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors achieve or exceed the required credibility level. (3) The single shortfall factor (Test conditions, achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) is offset by the documented rationale that dry ambient F1717 testing is the regulatory standard for this device class and represents the most conservative condition for titanium construct stiffness assessment. (4) The sensitivity analysis confirms that QoI predictions are robust to input parameter variation within realistic uncertainty bounds. (5) The provenance chain is complete from raw experimental data through FEA ensemble predictions to the validation metric calculations. The model is fit for the intended regulatory purpose of supporting 510(k) substantial equivalence demonstration for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "hasOffsetRationale": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/offset/test-conditions-shortfall",
      "type": "OffsetRationale",
      "name": "Offset rationale for Test conditions factor shortfall",
      "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-conditions",
      "justification": "The Test conditions factor achieved level 2 against a required level 3 because only a single test condition (ambient dry, quasi-static ASTM F1717) was evaluated. This shortfall is accepted for the following reasons: (a) The ASTM F1717 standard specifies ambient dry testing as the normative condition for pedicle screw construct evaluation; no regulatory guidance document for this device class requires wet or elevated-temperature F1717 validation. (b) Published literature (Nagaraja et al., 2012; ASTM STP 1530) demonstrates that titanium alloy construct stiffness and yield force are not significantly affected by physiological saline immersion at 37°C (< 2% difference), making the single ambient condition conservative and clinically representative. (c) The inter-laboratory design (two independent facilities) provides orthogonal evidence of test condition robustness that partially compensates for the absence of a second environmental condition. (d) The overall credibility evidence package — with 12 of 13 factors at or above required level and all QoI comparisons well within acceptance bounds — provides sufficient aggregate confidence to support the regulatory decision despite this single-factor shortfall."
